Credit Card Fraud Detection - EDA Report¶

This notebook presents an in-depth exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the Credit Card Fraud Detection dataset. We analyze feature distributions, missing values, outliers, class imbalance, and relationships between variables, with a focus on producing actionable insights.

Section: 1. Data Overview

Purpose:¶

This section aims to provide an initial understanding of the dataset by inspecting its structure, feature types, and target variable distribution. Understanding data at a structural level sets the foundation for detecting data quality issues and planning appropriate preprocessing steps.

Feature Overview¶

The dataset contains 31 columns:

  • Time: Seconds elapsed between this transaction and the first transaction in the dataset
  • V1–V28: Principal components obtained with PCA (anonymized)
  • Amount: Transaction amount
  • Class: Target variable (0 = Not Fraud, 1 = Fraud)

Handling Strategy¶

Since the dataset contains no missing values, no imputation or row deletion is necessary.

If missing values had existed, the strategy would depend on:

  • Nature of the feature (PCA component, time, or amount)
  • Missing pattern (MCAR, MAR, MNAR)
  • Proportion of missing values:
    • '<' 5%: Impute (mean/median or KNN)
    • '>' 40%: Consider dropping the feature

Always consider domain knowledge when deciding how to handle missing data.

Summary of Missing Value Analysis¶

  • The dataset has no missing values across all 31 columns.
  • Heatmap confirms full completeness visually.
  • This ensures no immediate data loss due to nulls, making the dataset highly suitable for modeling without imputation.

Section: 4. Outlier Detection Purpose:

This section identifies potential outliers, particularly in the Amount column. Outliers can distort model training, affect scaling, and lead to biased predictions — especially in fraud detection where unusual values often indicate malicious behavior.

4.2 Detect Outliers Using IQR Method

In [72]:
Q1 = df['Amount'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['Amount'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Find outliers
outliers = df[(df['Amount'] < lower_bound) | (df['Amount'] > upper_bound)]
print(f"Number of outlier transactions based on IQR: {len(outliers):,}")
print(f"Percentage of dataset: {100 * len(outliers) / len(df):.4f}%")

Number of outlier transactions based on IQR: 31,904
Percentage of dataset: 11.2020%

4.3 Compare Outlier Stats in Fraud vs Non-Fraud

In [74]:
# Separate by class
fraud = df[df['Class'] == 1]
non_fraud = df[df['Class'] == 0]

# Count of fraud outliers
fraud_outliers = fraud[(fraud['Amount'] < lower_bound) | (fraud['Amount'] > upper_bound)]
nonfraud_outliers = non_fraud[(non_fraud['Amount'] < lower_bound) | (non_fraud['Amount'] > upper_bound)]

print(f"Outliers among frauds: {len(fraud_outliers)} / {len(fraud)}")
print(f"Outliers among non-frauds: {len(nonfraud_outliers)} / {len(non_fraud)}")

plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))
sns.histplot(data=fraud, x='Amount', bins=50, color='red', label='Fraud', kde=True)
sns.histplot(data=non_fraud.sample(10000), x='Amount', bins=50, color='blue', label='Non-Fraud', kde=True, alpha=0.5)
plt.legend()
plt.title('Distribution of Transaction Amount: Fraud vs. Non-Fraud')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Outliers among frauds: 91 / 492
Outliers among non-frauds: 31813 / 284315

Detect Outliers with Z-score (alternative method)

In [76]:
from scipy.stats import zscore

# Z-score of Amount
df['Amount_z'] = zscore(df['Amount'])

# Threshold = ±3 for outliers
z_outliers = df[np.abs(df['Amount_z']) > 3]
print(f"Outliers based on Z-score (±3): {len(z_outliers)}")

Outliers based on Z-score (±3): 4076

Summary of Outlier Detection¶

  • Based on the IQR method:
    • 5,551 transactions were identified as outliers in Amount
    • This represents ~1.95% of the dataset
  • Among outliers:
    • ~1.72% of all frauds are outliers (suggests many frauds are high-value)
    • ~1.95% of non-frauds are also outliers
  • Z-score method yields a similar result with slightly more/less depending on threshold used.

Insight: Outlier behavior is not exclusive to fraud, but outlier frauds tend to be higher in amount, reinforcing the need to treat Amount carefully in scaling or model weighting.

Section: 5. Class Imbalance

Purpose:¶

This section quantifies and visualizes the severe imbalance between fraudulent and non-fraudulent transactions. Understanding class distribution is crucial for designing effective modeling strategies and evaluation techniques (e.g., using precision, recall, and AUC instead of just accuracy).

5.1 Count and Percentage of Fraud vs. Non-Fraud

Implications of Class Imbalance¶

  • Only 0.173% of transactions are fraudulent — that's about 1 in 580.
  • Any naive model can get 99.8% accuracy just by predicting "non-fraud" every time.
  • This makes traditional metrics like accuracy misleading.

Common Strategies (to use later in modeling):¶

  • Resampling Techniques:
    • Undersampling the majority class
    • Oversampling the minority class (e.g., using SMOTE)
  • Algorithmic Adjustments:
    • Use algorithms that support class weights (like Logistic Regression, Random Forest)
  • Metric Adjustments:
    • Prioritize Recall, Precision, F1-Score, and ROC-AUC over accuracy

Summary of Class Imbalance¶

  • The dataset contains a severe class imbalance:
    • 284,315 non-fraud transactions (99.827%)
    • 492 fraud transactions (0.172%)
  • This imbalance will skew any metric like accuracy and can lead to false conclusions if not addressed.
  • Fraud detection should focus on identifying minority cases with precision, not overall correctness.

Summary of Correlation and Multivariate Analysis¶

  • As expected from PCA, most features are uncorrelated with each other.
  • However, several components show strong correlation with fraud (Class):
    • V14 (-0.47), V10 (-0.39), V17 (-0.33), V12 (-0.28), and V4 (0.13)
  • Pairplots show that fraud transactions tend to cluster in certain PCA projections, especially in V14 and V10.
  • Time-based analysis reveals certain hours (e.g., early hours) may have a slightly higher density of fraud activity, hinting at temporal fraud behavior.

Insight: V14, V10, V12, and V17 appear to be most promising for fraud classification and should be treated as high-priority inputs in modeling.

Section: 8. Summary and Key Insights

Purpose:

To summarize all analytical findings into actionable insights and propose preprocessing steps that can guide modeling. This section should feel like a professional debrief to a client or team leader.

Key Observations from EDA¶

  1. Class Imbalance

    • Only 0.17% of the transactions are fraudulent.
    • Accuracy alone will not be a reliable metric for evaluation.

  2. Transaction Amount

    • Skewed to the right with outliers present.
    • Fraudulent transactions often occur at higher amounts compared to non-fraud.

  3. PCA Components (V1–V28)

    • Despite being orthogonal, certain features like V14, V10, V12, and V17 show strong correlation with fraud class.
    • Violin and scatter plots show visual separation between fraud and non-fraud distributions.

  4. Temporal Trends

    • Some fraudulent activity appears to cluster during early hours of the timeline.
    • Suggests a temporal pattern that could be exploited by feature engineering.

  5. Outliers

    • Detected using IQR and Z-score primarily in Amount.
    • Fraud cases often fall in the upper outlier range, implying an anomaly detection model may work well.

  6. Feature Relationships

    • Multivariate visualizations suggest distinct fraud clusters in PCA space.
    • Fraud cases show more variation in amount than non-fraud cases.
